{
  "doc_id": "21484",
  "text": "The genus Paracoccus (type species, Paracoccus denitrificans), first proposed by Davis et al. [CITATION_1] and emended by Ludwig et al. [CITATION_2] , Katayama et al. [CITATION_3] and Liu et al. [CITATION_4] , belongs to the family Rhodobacteraceae of the order Rhodobacterales in the Alphaproteobacteria. At the time of writing, the genus Paracoccus comprises 48 species with validly published names (www.bacterio.net/paracoccus.html; http://ijs.microbiologyresearch.org/content/journal/ijsem), which have been isolated from various environments, such as soil, bioreactor, activated sludge, root nodule, rhizosphere, cornetfish, coral, seawater, sea-sand, sediment and patient. Members of the genus Paracoccus are Gram-negative and oxidase-and catalase-positive, mesophilic, neutrophilic and non-halophilic, halophilic or halotolerant and have a high metabolic versatility. Chemotaxonomically, members of the genus are characterized by having ubiquinone-10 (Q-10) as the major respiratory quinone, C 18 : 1 !7c as the predominant fatty acid and DNA G+C contents between 64 and 70 mol%. The present study was carried out to clarify the taxonomic position of a novel species of the genus Paracoccus by a polyphasic taxonomic approach.",
